I have employed MinMaxScaler to rescale the dataset such that all feature values are in the range [0, 1] as shown in the table above. For each value, MinMaxScaler subtracts the minimum value in the feature and then devides by the range. The range is the difference between the original maximum and original minimum. MinMaxScaler preserves the shape of the original distribution.

Some descriptions regarding attributes¶

  1. Date: date in format dd/mm/yyyy
  2. Time: time in format hh:mm:ss
  3. Global active power: household global minute-averaged active power (in kilowatt)
  4. Global reactive power: household global minute-averaged active power (in kilowatt)
  5. Voltage: minute-averaged voltage (in volt)
  6. Gloabl intensity: household global minute-averaged current intensity (in ampere)
  7. Sub metering 1: energe sub-metering No.1 (in watt-hour of active energy). It corresponds to the kitchen, containing mainly a diswasher, an oven and a microwave (hot plates are not electric but gas powered).
  8. Sub metering 2: energy sub-metering No.2 (in watt-hour of active energy). It corresponds to the laundry room, containing a washing-machine, a tumble-drier, a refrigerator and a light.
  9. Sub metering 3: energy sub-metering No.3 (in watt-hour of active energy). It corresponds to an electric water-heater and an air-conditioner.

Correlations¶

In [50]:
import seaborn as sns; sns.set_theme()
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 12))   
ax = sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot = True)

The correlation coefficient is calculated to measure the statistical relationship or association between attributes of interest that are continuous data.

It's obvious that there aren't many highly correlated independent attributes. However, pairs of attributes give correlation coefficient values so near +/-1 and they suggest there to be a strong correlation.

Therefore, we will keep all of them for the model. However, year, month and day columns are not really useful, we will remove these three columns.

Boxplots¶

In [58]:

<Figure size 960x560 with 0 Axes>

A boxplot shows the distribution of data in a dataset. It provides information such as "minimum", first quartile (Q1), median, third quartile (Q3) and "maximum". It is useful as it provides a visual sumary of the data, enabling viewers to quickly identify mean values, the dispersion of dataset and signs of skewness.

Preparing Data for Machine Learning¶

Category Indexing, One-Hot Encoding and VectorAssembler - a feature transformer that merges multiple columns into a vector column.

In [67]:
from pyspark.ml.feature import OneHotEncoder, StringIndexer, VectorAssembler 
from pyspark.ml.regression import LinearRegression

df_sp = spark.createDataFrame(df)
train, test = df_sp.randomSplit([0.7, 0.3])

assemblerInputs = ['Global_reactive_power', 'Voltage', 'Global_intensity', 
               'Sub_metering_1', 'Sub_metering_2', 'Sub_metering_3']
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=assemblerInputs, outputCol="features")

lr = LinearRegression(maxIter = 100, regParam = 0.3, elasticNetParam = 0.8, 
                        featuresCol = 'features', labelCol = 'Global_active_power')

The above code are taken from databricks' official site.

The records in the dataset are ordered according to date and time and I have created a new column named "Index" to assign a number to each record.

Since the function randomSplit works for Spark dataframe, I have to convert my pandas dataframe back to Spark dataframe.

Next, we use the VectorAssembler to combine all the feature columns into a single vector column

Pipeline¶

We use Pipeline to chain multiple Transformers and Estimators together to specify our machine learning workflow. A Pipeline’s stages are specified as an ordered array.

In [68]:
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
pl = Pipeline(stages = [assembler, lr])
mod = pl.fit(test) # use train --> see example code to confirm Prac8

RMSE: 0.106699
r2: 0.000000

RMSE is a frequently used measure of the differences between values predicted by a model or an estimator and the values observed. It is the square root of the variance of the residuals. It indicates the absolute fit of the model to the data–how close the observed data points are to the model’s predicted values. Whereas R-squared is a relative measure of fit, RMSE is an absolute measure of fit. As the square root of a variance, RMSE can be interpreted as the standard deviation of the unexplained variance, and has the useful property of being in the same units as the response variable. Lower values of RMSE indicate better fit. RMSE is a good measure of how accurately the model predicts the response, and it is the most important criterion for fit if the main purpose of the model is prediction.

The RMSE is small which implies the model being a good fit of the actual values. However, this is contradictory as viewing the graph, the model prediction significantly differs from the actual values. The model is not working properly and I decide to do antoher evaluation using another method.

Decision Tree Classifier¶

Decision trees are widely used since they are easy to interpret, handle categorical features, extend to the multiclass classification setting, do not require feature scaling, and are able to capture non-linearities and feature interactions.
